Comments: Special Acct, Retirement Acct earn 4% interest wherelse Ordinary Acct earn 2.5% interest.  Transfer our SA to RA to top up to the Full Retirement Sum, and bal is then transferred to OA, which means we lose out in interest as OA earns lesser interest.  Also, not everybody reached their FRS, and mthly payouts rec'd is low, but we can withdraw fm SA to live by.  But fm 2025, scrapping off SA, we can only rec a fixed mthly payouts and had no means of withdrawal of some money fm SA when we need to.  Also, the 4% interest earned in RA will go to a common pool, so when we pass on, whatever be left in our RA after all the mthly payouts will then be disbursed to our nominated beneficiary, but not the 4% compounded interest earned as it will go to the common pool. Comments: What's the point in giving 40+ year olds that money? They're never going to use it. It'd be better spent on the 20+ year olds, especially the non-degree fellas. Any upskilling and reskilling that actually matter take time. A 40 hour part-time introductory course isn't going to land you any meaningful job that's not already within your current skillset. This age group won't go into unemployment for months and months to 'skill up'. If they have a job, they are holding on to it for dear life, because who knows when they're going to find another job at that age. And if they don't have a job, they need a job ASAP.  Singaporeans aren't rich enough to be forgoing paychecks to 'learn'. You have family, kids and house? Even more unlikely. Which is why it makes more sense to target the 20 year olds, because they have none of those burdens on their minds. SkillsFuture has been running for quite some time already.
